<Layout
  title="Deck Refloor — New Composite Boards on Your Existing Frame | Belvedere Decks"
  description="Deck resurfacing in Montgomery County, MD: premium TimberTech or Trex boards with hidden fasteners on your existing frame. $14,000–$20,000 typical. Honest frame inspection first."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Deck Refloor · $14,000–$20,000 typical</p>
      <h1>Your frame is fine. Your boards are done.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
      <p class="lead">
        If your deck's structure is sound but the surface is splintered, faded, or
        endlessly hungry for stain, a Refloor replaces the walking surface with premium
        composite — for a fraction of a full rebuild.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Is your deck a refloor candidate?</h2>
      <p>
        Most decks built in Montgomery County between 1985 and 2010 used pressure-treated
        framing that outlasts its boards by decades. We verify yours honestly, in front of
        you: the screwdriver test on posts and joists, the ledger flashing check where the
        deck meets your house, and joist spacing — composite boards require 16″ spacing
        (12″ for diagonal layouts), and we tell you plainly if yours doesn't qualify.
      </p>

      <h2>What's included</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Careful removal of existing boards, protecting your railings and framing</li>
        <li>Full substructure inspection — joists, beam, and ledger — for rot or damage</li>
        <li>Replacement of rotted or bowed joists (an allowance is stated in your contract, with any additional by written change order — never a surprise)</li>
        <li>New blocking secured around the perimeter</li>
        <li>Protective joist tape on top of every joist and beam — the detail that doubles frame life under composite</li>
        <li>Premium TimberTech or Trex boards with a hidden-fastener system — no exposed screws in the field</li>
        <li>Railings re-secured and safety-checked: 36″ height, ≤4″ baluster spacing</li>
        <li>Haul-away of all old boards and debris</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="notice">
        No building permit is typically required for a refloor — the framing stays in
        place. If we find structural work is needed, we confirm requirements with
        Montgomery County before anything changes, in writing.
      </div>

      <h2>The range, honestly</h2>
      <p>
        Typical 300–400 sq ft refloors run <strong>$14,000–$20,000</strong>. What moves it:
        board tier, joist condition, and stairs. You'll have your exact number, with three
        board options, before we leave the first visit.
      </p>
      <p><a class="btn primary" href="/contact">Get your refloor price</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
